<paragraph blockId="21.[123,651,1014,1741]" lastBlockId="21.[699,1228,193,1096]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
TAXONOMY: The Papallacta material closely resembles the 
<typeStatus box="[911,961,193,216]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">type</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1913" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Akodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="mollis" subSpecies="altorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Akodon mollis altorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as originally described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, O." pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="404 - 409" refId="ref25296" refString="Thomas, O. 1913. New forms of Akodon and Phyllotis, and a new genus for '' Akodon '' teguina. Annals and Magazine of Natural History 8 (11): 404 - 409." type="journal article" year="1913">Thomas (1913)</bibRefCitation>
based on a specimen collected at 
<quantity metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="m" value="2600.0">2600 m</quantity>
in the Ecuadorean province of 
<collectingRegion box="[1107,1178,281,304]" country="Ecuador" name="Canar" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Cañar</collectingRegion>
. No substantive analysis of character data, however, is available to support the current hypothesis (
<bibRefCitation author="Cabrera, A." box="[814,987,369,392]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="309 - 732" refId="ref21669" refString="Cabrera, A. 1961. Catalogo de los mamiferos de America del Sur. Revista del Museo Argentino de Ciencias Naturales '' Bernardino Rivadavia' ' (Ciencias Zoologicas) 4 (2): 309 - 732." type="journal article" year="1961">Cabrera, 1961</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Musser, G. G. &amp; M. D. Carleton" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="501 - 755" refId="ref23955" refString="Musser, G. G., and M. D. Carleton. 1993. Family Muridae. In D. E. Wilson and D. M. Reeder (editors), Mammal species of the world, 2 nd ed.: 501 - 755. Washington, DC: Smithsonian Institution Press." type="book chapter" year="1993">Musser and Carleton, 1993</bibRefCitation>
) that 
<emphasis box="[884,976,399,422]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">altorum</emphasis>
, a highland taxon, is really conspecific with the geographically adjacent lowland forms 
<taxonomicName authority="Thomas (1894)" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1894" box="[963,1227,457,480]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Akodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mollis">
<emphasis box="[963,1034,457,480]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">mollis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, O." box="[1045,1227,457,480]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="346 - 366" refId="ref24959" refString="Thomas, O. 1894. Descriptions of some new Neotropical Muridae. Annals and Magazine of Natural History 6 (14): 346 - 366." type="journal article" year="1894">Thomas (1894)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Hershkovitz (1940)" authorityName="Hershkovitz" authorityYear="1940" box="[750,1110,486,510]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Oligoryzomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fulvescens">
<emphasis box="[750,869,487,510]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">fulvescens</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hershkovitz, P." box="[878,1110,486,509]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="1 - 3" refId="ref22833" refString="Hershkovitz, P. 1940. Notes on the distribution of the akodont rodent, Akodon mollis, in Ecuador with a description of a new race. Occasional Papers of the Museum of Zoology, University of Michigan 418: 1 - 3." type="journal article" year="1940">Hershkovitz (1940)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. As noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Myers, P. &amp; J. L. Patton" box="[739,1042,516,539]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="1 - 35" refId="ref24077" refString="Myers, P., and J. L. Patton. 1989. Akodon of Peru and Bolivia - revision of the fumeus group (Rodentia: Sigmodontinae). Occasional Papers of the Museum of Zoology, University of Michigan 721: 1 - 35." type="journal article" year="1989">Myers and Patton (1989)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1894" box="[1057,1227,516,539]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Akodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mollis">
<emphasis box="[1057,1227,516,539]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Akodon mollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as currently recognized has a very large geographic range and exhibits substantial geographic variation. Given their conclusion that 
<emphasis box="[699,781,633,656]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">fumeus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, O." box="[794,974,633,656]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="125 - 143" refId="ref25218" refString="Thomas, O. 1902. On mammals from Cochabamba, Bolivia, and the region north of that place. Annals and Magazine of Natural History 7 (9): 125 - 143." type="journal article" year="1902">Thomas (1902)</bibRefCitation>
—another taxon formerly ranked as a subspecies or synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1894" box="[699,770,692,715]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Akodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mollis">
<emphasis box="[699,770,692,715]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">mollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
—is a valid species, a comprehensive revision of this complex is long overdue.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[699,1228,193,1096]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3395013329" collectionCode="FIELD, OBSERVATIONS" elevation="3880" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" specimenCount="16">
<collectionCode box="[728,968,750,773]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">FIELD OBSERVATIONS</collectionCode>
: The 
<specimenCount box="[1037,1195,750,773]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="generic">16 specimens</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1894" box="[699,868,780,803]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Akodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mollis">
<emphasis box="[699,868,780,803]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Akodon mollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that I collected near Papallacta in 1980 were trapped at elevations ranging from 
<quantity box="[764,954,838,861]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.88" metricValueMax="4.16" metricValueMin="3.6" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="m" value="3880.0" valueMax="4160.0" valueMin="3600.0">
<elevation box="[764,954,838,861]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.88" metricValueMax="4.16" metricValueMin="3.6" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="m" value="3880.0" valueMax="4160.0" valueMin="3600.0">3600 to 4160 m</elevation>
</quantity>
. Of these, 13 were taken in the shrubby páramo/forest ecotone, and 
<quantity box="[699,751,897,920]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="in" value="3.0">3 in</quantity>
grassy páramo. All recorded captures were on the ground: 
<quantity box="[951,998,926,949]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="in" value="5.0">5 in</quantity>
tunnels among the bases of tall bunch grass, 5 among wet litter under mossy shrubs, 
<quantity box="[962,1012,985,1008]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="in" value="4.0">4 in</quantity>
runways through mixed bunch grass and bushes, 
<quantity box="[1080,1127,1014,1037]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
a rabbit trail beneath low herbaceous cover, and 1 beneath an earth bank
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
